solutions:
Let region j be when V = V and define $k_j=\frac{1}{\hbar} \sqrt{2 m\left(E-V_j\right)}$, which is real and positive since E > V for all j. Schrdingers equation in region j reads $(\frac{d^2}{dx^2} + k_j^2) \psi_j (x) = 0$ whose solution is $A_j e^{ik_j x} + B_j e^{-ik_j x}$, where A is right-moving and B is left-moving.

Let region 2 extend from x = -a to x = 0. Since the potential is finite everywhere, the wavefunction and its derivative must be continuous everywhere. This implies

$$
A_1 e^{-ik_1 a} + B_1 e^{ik_1 a} = A_2 e^{-ik_2 a} + B_2 e^{ik_2 a}, \tag{23.2.1a}
$$

$$
k_1 A_1 e^{-ik_1 a} - k_1 B_1 e^{ik_1 a} = k_2 A_2 e^{-ik_2 a} - k_2 B_2 e^{ik_2 a}, \tag{23.2.1b}
$$

$$
A_2 + B_2 = A_3 + B_3, \tag{23.2.1c}
$$

$$
k_2 A_2 - k_2 B_2 = k_3 A_3 - k_3 B_3. \tag{23.2.1d}
$$

We can use (23.2.1a) and (23.2.1b) to solve for A and B in terms of A and B or A and B.
This is summarized in matrix form as

$$
\binom{A_2}{B_2}=\frac{1}{2 k_2}\left(\begin{array}{rr}
\left(k_1+k_2\right) e^{-i\left(k_1-k_2\right) a} & -\left(k_1-k_2\right) e^{i\left(k_1+k_2\right) a} \\
-\left(k_1-k_2\right) e^{-i\left(k_1+k_2\right) a} & \left(k_1+k_2\right) e^{i\left(k_1-k_2\right) a}
\end{array}\right)\binom{A_1}{B_1}, \tag{23.2.2a}
$$

$$
\begin{pmatrix}
A_2 \\
B_2
\end{pmatrix}
= \frac{1}{2k_2}
\begin{pmatrix}
k_2 + k_3 & k_2 - k_3 \\
k_2 - k_3 & k_2 + k_3
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
A_3 \\
B_3
\end{pmatrix}. \tag{23.2.2b}
$$

Setting these two equal to each allows us to solve for A and B in terms of A and B. After a lot of tedious algebra, we find $\binom{A_3}{B_3}=\mathbf{M}\binom{A_1}{B_1}$, where

$$
M_{11}=M_{22}^*=\frac{1}{2 k_2 k_3} e^{-i k_1 a}\left[\left(k_1+k_3\right) k_2 \cos \left(k_2 a\right)+i\left(k_1 k_3+k_2^2\right) \sin \left(k_2 a\right)\right], \tag{23.2.3a}
$$

$$
M_{12}=M_{21}^*=-\frac{1}{2 k_2 k_3} e^{i k_1 a}\left[\left(k_1-k_3\right) k_2 \cos \left(k_2 a\right)+i\left(k_1 k_3-k_2^2\right) \sin \left(k_2 a\right)\right] . \tag{23.2.3b}
$$

M is called the *transfer matrix* and relates the coefficients on the right of the region where V is changing to the coefficients on the left. We want $\binom{B_1}{A_3}=\mathrm{S}\binom{A_1}{B_3}$. The two are related by simply writing out the equation involving M and solving for B and A in terms of A and B (in that order) instead. One finds

$$
S = \frac{1}{M_{22}}
\begin{pmatrix}
-M_{21} & 1 \\
\text{det } M & M_{12} 
\end{pmatrix}. \tag{23.2.3}
$$

After some algebra, one finds det M to be

$$
\text{det } M = k_1 / k_3. \tag{23.2.4}
$$

For leftward scattering, B = 0, and the transmission coefficient is

$$
T_l=\frac{\left|A_3\right|^2}{\left|A_1\right|^2}=\left|S_{21}\right|^2=\frac{4 k_1^2 k_2^2}{\left(k_1+k_3\right)^2 k_2^2 \cos ^2\left(k_2 a\right)+\left(k_1 k_3+k_2^2\right)^2 \sin ^2\left(k_2 a\right)} \tag{23.2.5}
$$
